       <a href="http://savetheelephants.org/"> <h2 id="sec5">Save the Elephants</h2></a>
       <p>Karma Grove's sales have generated 50 dollars for the Wildlife Conservation Network's Safe the Elephants (S.T.E.) foundation. S.T.E. is one of the largest and most effective on-the-ground anti-poaching programs in the world.</p>

       <p>Illegal poaching and game hunting have led to the critically-endangered African Elephant population's rapid decline in recent years. The species is on the verge of total extinction, a tragedy that will become reality in just a few years time without an even stronger effort.</p>

       <p>In response, S.T.E. has increased its efforts to take both a hands-on/on-the-ground approach to physically protect these beautiful animals, as well as encourage the bonds of local and international policy to end the threat. In whole, S.T.E. is making a holistic effort at protecting one of the world's greatest treasures.</p>

       <p>A primary focus of S.T.E. is curbing both the supply and demand of the ivory market in China. China is the world's hub for such brutal and despicable activity. According to a <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/13/opinion/stop-chinas-ivory-trade.html?_r=0">November 6, 2014 release by The New York Times</a>, <i>China buys 70 percent of the illegally poached African elephant tusks for use by its government factories to manufacture jewelry and trinkets like bookmarks, rings, figurines, combs, chopsticks and religious sculptures.</i></p>

       <p>
        To help stop this superflous slaughter, Save the Elephants has scaled up it's anti-poaching programs in Kenya's Samburu National Reserve. The organization is also working with Kenyan Wildlife Service and local communities to end this travesty.
      </p>

